{
  "text": "Stretch-induced depolarization could result from inhibition of any of the various K ϩ currents identified in smooth muscle [CITATION_1] , provided the channel was active when the vessel had basal vascular tone. A direct role for a K ϩ channel in initiating the myogenic response has not been shown (see Table 2 ), but there is evidence that K ϩ currents can and do counteract myogenic tone. Of the five major types of K ϩ currents identified in VSM (267), three appear to play no significant role in the myogenic response: the inward rectifier K ϩ channel, the ATP-sensitive (K ATP ) K ϩ channel (294), and a novel K ϩ channel (K N ) with kinetics similar to M-type neuronal current [CITATION_2] . Indirect evidence at first suggested a role for K ATP channels in the response of the coronary microcirculation to a fall in perfusion pressure [CITATION_3] , but recently a more direct study failed to show a significant effect of K ATP channel antagonists on isolated small arteries at any pressure [CITATION_4] . However, there is evidence that the other two types of channels, voltage-dependent K ϩ (K v ) channels and Ca 2ϩ -activated K ϩ (K Ca ) channels, can provide potentially powerful repolarizing mechanisms to counteract stimuli resulting from VSM stretch. The K v channels exhibit exponential increases in open probability upon depolarization and likely serve an important role in the repolarization of excitable cells [CITATION_5] . K v channel blockers depolarize VSM cells in pressurized arterioles and augment myogenic tone [CITATION_6] . K Ca channels are activated both by increases in [Ca 2ϩ ] i and by depolarization. The function of large-conductance K Ca (BK) channels is particularly important to determine because activation of only a few channels would be sufficient to effect large changes in the membrane potential of a VSM cell (due to the high input resistance). For this reason, there is a substantial amount of information concerning the role of BK channels in the myogenic response.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "17785593",
    "[CITATION_2]": "25932763",
    "[CITATION_3]": "29194352",
